Love Report 2: More Love, More Report, More 2¶

Date: Feb 14 2023

Hello Valentine! It's been a long time since the last love report, and as a 50% shareholder in the relationship, you almost have a voting majority on the board just by yourself, so your opinion is very important! So, here it is!

Now, a repeat favorite from last time: plotting the messages over time!¶

It's cool to see the breaks like that! This is an interesting limitation of this analysis, and of many analyses - the most interesting stuff, the stuff I really wish I could dive into, is the stuff in these gaps.¶

The best conversations we have are always in person, and it occurs to me that in a way, this chart almost measures exactly the opposite of what it seems like it might. It's highest at the snowy, thin-air-gives-me-a-headache peak of Mt. Holy Fuck I Just Met You, but at that point, we barely knew each other, really. It drops down to zero during the parts of our lives where we've really had the time to just chill out and be near each other - it's lower during Duke than it is now, showing that our jobs have taken some time, and I think the jagged sawtooth of the last year of data is the weekly cycle of us getting to talk to each other more over the weekend.¶

Here's an interesting thought: what else happened over that time, in our lives? I did some googling and some math, and it turns out that over our 1195 days:¶

  • Each of us has farted around 15000-25000 times, if we're average. The other one would have heard probably around 1000-1500 of them.
  • We've spent about 4000 hours sleeping next to each other.
  • Earth has moved around 14,053,200,000 miles, relative to the center of the galaxy. We've come a long way! :)
  • Each of our hearts has beat around 119,500,000 times - all of mine for you. <3

How have we been feeling? I'm going to run a day-by-day sentiment analysis across the messages. This isn't a super reliable method, but it'll give us some idea.¶

In the last report, going to the actual messsages made this seem a little silly. But still, it's interesting that right at the start of LDR is our peak daily sentiment, so lets look at that day.¶

Again, this isn't a fantastic mathematical system - it was an 'average of one' situation here, that was the only text message sent that day. Still - I like it. It's actually just before we started LDR. Here's one of those up close:¶

So, it's still not an amazing analysis. If you look back at the chart, though, there is something interesting that I see. Before reunification, sentiments seem to never drop as low as they do after reunification. There's a couple interpretations that are possible here:¶

  1. We got sadder after reuniting. I think we both know that's not true. LDR was kind of miserable.
  2. The more sad thoughts over LDR weren't shared, and they are now. This is possible, and it would mean that we're connecting better now than we were. I don't think this is likely as number 3, though, because I think we usually don't do hard/bad stuff over text, LDR or not.
  3. The good stuff used to be shared over text, and now, it's shared in person. By removing some of the good stuff from the text, it makes it look like our sentiment is lower, but actually, those things are shared in person. I like the sound of that one! :)
